  "notes": [
    {
      "title": "Feminine Word Formation",
      "titleArabic": "تَأْنِيثُ الْكَلِمَات",
      "content": [
        "Most masculine nouns and adjectives can be made feminine by adding ة (taa marbuta). This applies to professions, descriptions, and many other words.",
        "Feminine verbs in the past tense add تْ to the end: ذَهَبَ (he went) becomes ذَهَبَتْ (she went). The ت takes sukūn (no vowel)."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Add ة to make most words feminine: طَالِبٌ → طَالِبَةٌ",
        "Feminine past tense adds تْ: كَتَبَ → كَتَبَتْ (she wrote)",
        "Some words have unique feminine forms (not just adding ة)",
        "When the verb comes before a feminine subject, it takes تِ: ذَهَبَتِ الطَّالِبَةُ"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "طَالِبَةٌ", "english": "female student" },
        { "arabic": "مُدَرِّسَةٌ", "english": "female teacher" },
        { "arabic": "ذَهَبَتْ", "english": "she went" },
        { "arabic": "كَتَبَتِ الْمُدَرِّسَةُ", "english": "The female teacher wrote" }
      ]
    }
  ],
